TY  - JOUR
T1  - Managerialist and Human Capital Explanations for Key Executive Pay Premiums: A Contingency Perspective
AU  - Combs, James G.
AU  - Skill, Maura S.
Y1  - 2003/02/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/30040676
DO  - 10.5465/30040676
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 63
EP  - 73
VL  - 46
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Managerialism is a theory that suggests that managers extract pay premiums by gaining control over their firms' compensation processes. Human capital theory suggests instead that pay premiums reflect executives' superior managerial abilities. This study tests a contingency perspective in which the source of pay premiums depends on executives' power and firms' governance strength. Results suggest pay premiums are a consequence of human capital in some firms and managerial entrenchment in others. Several implications are offered to guide future inquiry.
AB  - Managerialism is a theory that suggests that managers extract pay premiums by gaining control over their firms' compensation processes. Human capital theory suggests instead that pay premiums reflect executives' superior managerial abilities. This study tests a contingency perspective in which the source of pay premiums depends on executives' power and firms' governance strength. Results suggest pay premiums are a consequence of human capital in some firms and managerial entrenchment in others. Several implications are offered to guide future inquiry.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/30040676
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/30040676
Y2  - 2026/04/24
